"begin": 722, "end": 726}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4773"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NFAT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9903568625450134, "span": {"begin": 789, "end": 793}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5534"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "calcineurin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9900318384170532, "span": {"begin": 797, "end": 808}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4773"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NFAT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9214386343955994, "span": {"begin": 859, "end": 863}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3726"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AP-1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.990515947341919, "span": {"begin": 864, "end": 868}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "promoter region", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.742913007736206, "span": {"begin": 884, "end": 899}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3558"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "IL-2 genes", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9738531708717346, "span": {"begin": 903, "end": 913}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8354573249816895, "span": {"begin": 932, "end": 939}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3607"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "IL", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 978, "end": 980}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8745139837265015, "span": {"begin": 1019, "end": 1026}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3565"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-4", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9393021464347839, "span": {"begin": 1030, "end": 1034}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3558"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9759105443954468, "span": {"begin": 1107, "end": 1111}}], "text": "Localized nuclear factor of activated T cells (NFAT) in the nucleus of T cells forms complexes with activator protein-1 (AP-1) at the Interleukin (IL)-2 promoter region (Schreiber and Crabtree 1992; Jain et al. 1992), which induces transcription of IL-2 (Jain et al. 1993). In addition to IL-2, NFAT localized in the nucleus of T cells also binds to the promoter region of the other classes of cytokines including IL-4 and IL-13.  For IL-2, NFAT proteins are necessary for IL-2 gene expression and interaction of NFAT with AP-1 is required for IL-2 gene transcription. For IL-4, At least five different NFAT sites have been described in the IL-4 promoter with at least three of them being composite sites binding NFAT and AP-1 (Maci&aacute;n et al. 2001).  Lowered nuclear localization of NFAT by calcineurin inhibitor (CNI) results in decreased formation of NFAT/AP-1 complex at the promoter region of IL-2 genes in the nucleus of T cells thereby reducing the transcription of IL-2 (Dumont et al. 1998). Production in T cells of IL-4 and other classes of cytokines is also suppressed in the same manner as IL-2 (Dumont et al. 1998).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:54:24 +0000 2026"}